post_text:
Elementary Parents,
We are excited to see your children next week!! Please remember to use the bus drive on the east side of the building for morning drop-off at 7:55 a.m. (9:00 next week only). Please be patient as you may encounter a line of traffic but know that we will do our best to complete the process as quickly as possible. We will meet you in the bus drive to do temperature checks...students with a temperature of less than 100.4 will be allowed to enter the building. Students will report directly to their classrooms where breakfast will be served. Upon dismissal at 3:35, faculty and staff will escort students outside to board the bus or be picked up by parent/guardian. We appreciate your support as we begin the 2020-2021 school year!!! 🦅

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures.

Families who received SNAP benefits for the month of March 2020 and have children 5-18 years old as of May 17, 2020, do not need to apply for those children. If you did not receive SNAP in March 2020, you will need to fill out an online application. Follow the link below. Families will get up to $285 per child.

https://yourtexasbenefits.com/Learn/PEBT

post_text:
Due to circumstances that canceled all UIL academic competitions, UIL offered an At-Home Experience. This was not an official competition and did not lead to official awards or points. Students had opportunity to test their knowledge and skills.
Senior, Zoe Velasquez placed 1st in News Writing and 1st in Feature Writing in her level one group and advanced to the second level of competition.
In the Statewide Level Two for Small Schools, Zoe placed 6th in Feature Writing.
Congratulations, Zoe!

post_text: Here’s a fun game! Can you identify who is in this picture? Tori Vaughn found this old photograph of O’Donnell High School and the homecoming court of 1930 (approximate year?). Her family lived in the O’Donnell area beginning in 1906. Four names are noted on the back (Gene Gardenhire, Dick Tune, Summer Clayton, and Louis Miles). If anyone knows more about this photo or the individuals, it would be wonderful to discover.

post_text:
OHS 2020 SENIOR:
🎓 AARON OLIVAN 🎓 My name is Aaron Jacob Olivan. I am 17 years old, and the son of Scottie and Christie Olivan. I was born and raised in Tahoka before I decided to finish my senior year in O’Donnell.

At O’Donnell, I have participated in Football, Basketball, and Baseball. I was also involved in UIL Calculator Applications and Mathematics. With my first and last year being here in O’Donnell, I was inducted into the National Honor Society and have been a great role model to younger students. My proudest moments in O’Donnell would have to be is communicating with the staff and teachers and being able to have a strong connection with each of them.

This summer I plan on attending Southwest Texas Junior College and try to walk on their basketball team. I will pursue a Bachelor’s Degree in Education. 🦅

post_text:
Stay Well, Texas!
Coughing & sneezing can send tiny infected droplets into the air which can be inhaled by anyone within 6 feet of us. Always cough or sneeze into a tissue or your elbow and immediately wash your hands to lessen the risk of spreading the virus. Be smart. Stay well! #StayHomeTexas

Toser y estornudar puede llevar gotas infectadas al aire, que pueden ser inhaladas por personas que estén a 6 pies de ti. Siempre tosa o estornude en pañuelos desechables o en el codo y lávese las manos para disminuir la propagación del virus. ¡Mantente sano! #StayHomeTexas

shared_text:
Texas 1A Fan
April 10 at 9:47 AM ·

1A Senior Celebration spotlights Elvis Garces from Odonnell ISD!

Honors:
- State CX Debate
- FCCLA Culinary math (2nd region) (State)
- FFA creed (9th)
- Student council (president)
- Basketball:
District offensive mvp
Garden City Tournament MVP (career high of 31 pts)
All Region TSMCA 1st team
All state TSMCA 2nd team
TABC ALL REGION
ALL STAR game nominee

My favorite activity out and inside of school would have to be playing basketball, “literally can not get him to stay home instead of being in the gym.” -mom

Honestly being from a 1A school was the best experience possible. Kinda makes it cool to know that every imprint you make the little ones see and follow in that footstep. The community is so close you get a waive or “hi” no matter who or where you are. The love and support is overwhelming; i would say that 1A schools are the best schools.

#COVID19 lives on droplets in the lungs of people with the virus, even if they don’t have symptoms. When infected people breathe, the virus enters the air. If you can’t #StayHome, wear a mask/scarf/bandana, stay 6 feet apart, and wash your hands. #DontGoViral

#COVID19 lives on droplets in the lungs of people with the virus, even if they don’t have symptoms. When infected people breathe, the virus enters the air. If you can’t #StayHome, wear a mask/scarf/bandana, stay 6 feet apart, and wash your hands. #DontGoViral

#COVID19 vive de gotas en los pulmones de las personas con el virus incluso si no tienen síntomas. Cuando las personas contagiadas respiran, el virus entra al aire. Si no puedes quedarte en casa #StayHome, use una bufanda/pañuelo, manténgase a 6 pies de distancia y lávese las manos.

post_text:
Common symptoms of #COVID19 are fever, dry cough, & shortness of breath. If you have mild symptoms, call your doctor & #StayHome. If you develop serious symptoms, such as trouble breathing, pressure in the chest, or bluish lips or face, call your doctor & seek care immediately.

Los síntomas comunes de #COVID19 son fiebre, tos seca y dificultad para respirar.Si tiene síntomas leves, llame a su médico y quedate en casa. Si desarrolla síntomas graves, como dificultad para respirar o presión en el pecho, busque atención médica de inmediato. #StayHome

OHS 2020 SENIOR SPOTLIGHT:
🎓 ELVIS GARCES 🎓 My name is Elvis Garces, and I am the 18 year-old son of Elvis Garces and Mela Moralez.

I have attended O’Donnell ISD since Pre-K. My plans after high school are to attend South Plains College for my basics then hopefully transfer to Texas Tech to pursue a career in Kinesiology.

All my achievements have been a memory that I will never forget. However, my biggest accomplishments would have to be my achievements earned my senior year of basketball and the fact that we made it to the regional tournament. I was awarded District Offensive MVP, MVP of the Garden City tournament (career high of 31 pts), All-Region TSMCA 1st team, TSMCA All State 2nd team, and TABC All Region Team. Another amazing part of high school would have to be getting the lead of The Diviners and receiving All Star cast every performance. Getting the lead gave me the confidence to get out of my bubble.

I hope that what I did in high school is a strong example for kids younger to follow. 🦅

Marcos has attended O’Donnell ISD since Kindergarten and loves being an Eagle. Marcos plans to attend Texas A&M University in College Station Texas after graduating high school to major in Construction Science. One of Marcos’ greatest memories of high school was being a part of the OHS Sports Program for three years. One of his greatest accomplishments was being a part of the OHS Culinary and BBQ teams and advancing to State with his delicious BBQ chicken. Marcos one day also hopes to have his own food truck and make people happy with his great food and his sense of humor.

Marcos would like to leave this to the Senior Class of 2020: “improvise, adapt, and overcome.”

OHS 2020 SENIOR SPOTLIGHT:
🎓 BRIANNA SAUSEDA 🎓 My name is Brianna Ry’Ann Sauseda. I am 17 years old, and I am the proud daughter of Fred and Lori Vitolas. Born and raised in Lamesa, Texas, I have been to 2 different schools before I found my forever home at O’Donnell ISD.

At O’Donnell, I have participated in UIL Academic Poetry, Calculator Applications, Mathematics, Number Sense, and Accounting. I have also volunteered in the O’Donnell Student Council and have been in National Honor Society both for 3 years. Starting my Junior year, I became an O’Donnell Youth League Assistant Basketball Coach. Beginning my sophomore year, I began to take Dual Credit courses through South Plains College and am currently on my way to graduating with my Associate’s Degree come May 2020. Some of my proudest moments have been being inducted into the Phi Theta Kappa Honor Society for South Plains College and making the Dean’s Honor Roll List there as well.

In the summer of 2020, I plan on signing with and attending Lubbock Christian University to pursue a Bachelor/Master’s Degree in Accounting. 🦅

MARCH 31 UPDATE
Good morning, O'Donnell!
It is great to see our students working at home on Facebook! Please continue to post pictures because our teachers miss their students and want to see their faces!

The Grab and Go meals continue today from 10:00 - 12:00. Please go pick up a free lunch and breakfast from our fantastic cafeteria staff. These meals are provided to any child through age 18.

All school buildings are closed now, but our staff can be reached by email which are linked to the OISD webpage.

The Distance Learning from home will be extended through April 10 at OISD. Closures may be extended beyond that, and OISD will keep you informed through the School App, the OISD webpage, and the Screamin' Eagle Facebook page.

Stay safe, and continue the learning!

We have some exciting news to share, O’Donnell! Allison Hancock is joining our staff next year as our new Lady Eagle head basketball coach! 🦅 🏀

Some of you may recognize Coach Hancock because she grew up in O’Donnell and graduated from O’Donnell High School. She then played basketball at Clarendon College before she transferred and graduated from West Texas A&M University.

Coach Hancock has been at San Saba ISD for three years, teaching Algebra 1, 7th-8th grade math, and assistant cross country, basketball, and softball coach.

She is excited to be moving back home, and we are even more excited to welcome her to our amazing staff!

post_text:
Can we get a big THANK YOU out to our technology director, Pam Wilson?! In the face of moving an entire school district to online learning in just a matter of days, Mrs. Wilson had a school website that was already top notch and ready for teachers to create web pages, she got iPads and computers cleaned, loaded with needed apps, and sorted for all of our students, and she has helped each of us with our endless questions. Thanks, Mrs. Wilson, for making this week easier than expected!

If you want to be able to contact Mrs. Wilson with technology questions, join her Remind by texting @oisdt to 81010.
text:
Can we get a big THANK YOU out to our technology director, Pam Wilson?! In the face of moving an entire school district to online learning in just a matter of days, Mrs. Wilson had a school website that was already top notch and ready for teachers to create web pages, she got iPads and computers cleaned, loaded with needed apps, and sorted for all of our students, and she has helped each of us with our endless questions. Thanks, Mrs. Wilson, for making this week easier than expected!

If you want to be able to contact Mrs. Wilson with technology questions, join her Remind by texting @oisdt to 81010.

post_text: IMPORTANT ANNOUNCEMENT
text: IMPORTANT ANNOUNCEMENT

post_text:
Dear Parents of OISD Students,

In light of the rapidly changing reports on the coronavirus, we would like for all of our OISD families to start preparing for the possibility of a move to online instruction.

I will be sending out more information very soon, but in the meantime, if you do not have internet access at home, contact Poka Lambro at 806-924-7234 and tell them you have a student enrolled in O'Donnell ISD. Poka Lambro is committed to ensuring all students in their service area have access to the Internet. There will be no cost for installation. You do not have to have a phone line to have Internet. Thank you to Poka Lambro for offering this help to our community!

Dr. Catherine York Palmer
O'Donnell ISD Superintendent

post_text:
Cheer try-outs will be held on Wednesday, March 11th. Student body voting will be held during secondary’s activity period. Parents are welcome to come watch, however, recording and posting is not allowed. Tryouts for judges will begin at 3:15.
Please understand this is a one on one tryout process and no parents are allowed during this round. Each contestant will perform three consecutive jumps, an individual cheer, and “Two Bits” as a group. Contestants should be prepared to answer a question for judges.
Attire: Black Shorts, an Eagle Shirt or White shirt.
Please pull hair up in a ponytail away from your face.

The tryout cheers are posted on the O’Donnell ISD website.

http://odonnell.esc17.net/page/Cheer%20Videos

Please Contact Coach Krista, or myself if you have any questions.
Thank You,
Tammy Dempsey
